<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[264,1323,1299,1565]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,445,1299,1325]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Etymology</emphasis>
. The name of this species derives from the word Maya, a reference to the ancient populations living in the Yucatán peninsula and some other southern Central American areas from about 
<number box="[591,657,1379,1405]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1.5">1,500</number>
B.C. to about 
<number box="[828,894,1379,1405]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1.5">1,500</number>
A.D.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[264,1323,1299,1565]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,454,1419,1445]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Comments.</emphasis>
The male terminalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[755,884,1419,1444]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Anapausis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mayana">
<emphasis box="[755,884,1419,1444]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">A. mayana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are exceptionally simple, compared with other species of the genus, a condition acquired by some degree of simplification of the generic groundplan pattern. The shape of the gonostyles, parameres, and the S 
<number box="[1290,1320,1499,1525]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="10.0">10</number>
sclerites allows its immediate differentiation from 
<taxonomicName box="[856,959,1539,1564]" class="Insecta" family="Scatopsidae" genus="Anapausis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wirthi">
<emphasis box="[856,959,1539,1564]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">A. wirthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
